  "summary": "As the investigation into Arai's murder continues, the circle of suspects initially appears to include nearly everyone present. While Wooden Shinsuke jokingly suggests himself as a suspect, the focus shifts to the housekeeper, Kubo Haruko. Haruko, appearing pale and exhausted, testifies that she was in the kitchen with the maid, Hina, preparing lunch. Hina corroborates this, stating they were in the kitchen from approximately 10:10 until 10:40, during which time they could hear Mr. Yamada repairing the stairs. This testimony establishes alibis for both Haruko and Hina.\n\nIn contrast, the investigation into the Inagaki family relatives yields no solid alibis. Gan-ya claims he heard nothing due to soundproofing; Mizuki claims she did not notice Akiyama passing through the courtyard; and Shizuka claims he was walking in the outer courtyard for an hour but fails to explain a bag he was carrying. Detective Jiroh expresses frustration at the lack of progress, but Muto suggests the investigation has gained a new direction regarding the victim's side. Muto posits that the killer may have been aware of Mizuki's presence in the courtyard and suggests the possibility that Arai himself might have overlooked something important.\n\nThe narrative also provides historical context regarding the Oyama family and Kurenaga Castle. After World War II, the mansion became a villa. Twenty-five years prior, the former president, Oyama Motoharu, and his wife, Hinata, moved there to live in seclusion. They hired Yashiro as a housekeeper to care for them while their three sons were stationed in various cities.",
